Hey Carter, I just randomly came to your channel and just randomly started loving the videos. I still haven't finished watching this and the moment you were asking for suggestions for the battery in this video I thought I'll share what I practice.

I bought a Mac about 5 months ago and the battery is still at 100% capacity with 63 charge cycles using 2 very simple habit that I've shared below.

Firstly, heat is the biggest battery killer so just try to make sure your phone doesn't get that warm, or if they are warm, try not to use them.

Secondly these batteries love to stay around 50%. Keeping them near 0% / 100% for long durations stresses the chemicals inside these batteries and causes to degrade faster. So try to keep them between 20-80%, or 30-70%, and so on. 20-80% is more realistic.

I personally will be getting the Air. I think people forget that this is its own product, not meant to be the best of the best in the lineup. For me personally, I do not need all the camera functions that come on the other models as I only take photos to capture moments and memories in a snap. When it comes to the battery, I usually always have access to a charger of some sort at home, the car, work etc... Plus I do not use my phone for extensive things other then texting, calling, social media, and the occasional lowkey games. I doubt I will have any true problems with the battery life, and if I do end up getting the MagSafe charger it would be for some vacations or all-day activities and even so I doubt I will need it considering my phone usage. The thinness and weight is a bonus for me, considering all of the things I mentioned above!

Here‚Äôs my honest take on iPhone 17 vs iPhone 16 Pro:

When you‚Äôre buying a Pro model, you need at least 256GB storage. In sales, the iPhone 16 Pro (256GB) might drop to around ‚Çπ80K, but the chances of actually getting it at that price are less than 5% ‚Äî within minutes it usually shoots back up to ‚Çπ95K‚Äì1L. So realistically, it‚Äôs very hard to grab at the lowest deal.

Now comparing iPhone 17 vs 16 Pro:

Both have the same ProMotion 120Hz display.

iPhone 17 has a better selfie camera compared to 16 Pro.

17 offers better Wi-Fi connectivity, network bands, and signal reception.

Higher brightness outdoors on 17 vs 16 Pro.

Better battery life on 17, same size as 16 Pro.

Drawbacks with the 17:

Build quality ‚Üí 16 Pro has titanium, 17 has aluminum (but 17 runs cooler and with better efficiency).

16 Pro gives an extra telephoto lens + optical zoom.

16 Pro has Pro video features (ProRes RAW, SSD recording etc.) which 98% of regular users won‚Äôt ever use.

So the bottom line:

If you can grab the 16 Pro 256GB around ‚Çπ80K‚Äì90K, that‚Äôs hands down the best deal.

But once it crosses the ‚Çπ1L mark, it makes more sense to go for the iPhone 17 instead. (17 is the new pro)

Definitely avoid choosing the older 16 or 15 base models ‚Äî the iPhone 17 is the smarter choice for most regular users.

Has anyone noticed how it feels like someone at Apple sat down with their team and held a meeting titled: "How do we make sure the iPhone 17 Pro series doesn‚Äôt end up as the worst upgrade in Apple‚Äôs history?"

And the result? Remove the iPhone 17 Plus model ‚Äî that way, the 17 Pro series feels more important. Now, if someone wants a bigger screen or longer battery life, they're forced to go for the Pro models.

Honestly, if Apple had released the 17 Plus this year, most people (about 95%) wouldn‚Äôt need the Pro series. The Plus model would've had everything 95% user actually cares about ‚Äî a larger display and better battery life. But now, if you want just those two things, you're forced to pay for the Pro Max ‚Äî even if you don‚Äôt care about the ‚ÄúPro‚Äù features.

To those saying the Pro Max offers more ‚Äî sure, but let‚Äôs be real. Years ago, the difference between base and Pro models was meaningful. Now, Apple is clearly out of ideas but still wants to keep the high price tag. So they play these games: removing the Plus model to protect Pro sales, locking popular features behind more expensive models, and pretending it‚Äôs all about innovation.

Instead of admitting they can‚Äôt justify four iPhones a year anymore, Apple could‚Äôve just offered two: one compact and one large. Then maybe introduce a true foldable and call that the real Pro model. But they‚Äôre not interested in actual tech progress ‚Äî only higher revenue.

They even introduced a new ‚ÄúSlim‚Äù model to sit awkwardly between the 17 and 17 Pro, just to make the Pro look more attractive. And of course, they bumped up the Pro‚Äôs price too. So now your choices are:
- Get the basic iPhone 17, or
- Pay a lot more for the Pro ‚Äî even if all you wanted was a bigger battery and screen.

It‚Äôs clear Apple doesn‚Äôt want to be a leading tech innovator anymore. They want to be a luxury brand, charging premium prices for features that should be standard ‚Äî keeping things exclusive, not accessible.

Now compare pricing. In the U.S., the iPhone 17 Pro Max is somewhat in line with the Galaxy S25 Ultra. But in India? The Pro Max is almost the same price as the upcoming Galaxy Fold 7. That‚Äôs crazy. For Indian buyers, the S25 Ultra is way cheaper than the Pro Max ‚Äî and if someone has a Pro Max budget, it makes more sense to just spend a little extra and get the Fold 7, which is a real innovation leap.

People often say taxes cause this, but remember ‚Äî both iPhones and Samsung phones are now assembled in India. Neither is an Indian brand. So why is the price gap between them so much bigger in India than in the U.S.?

Honestly, I hope more Indians stop buying the Pro Max. Apple clearly isn‚Äôt thinking about users anymore ‚Äî just profits. I‚Äôm not saying it should be cheap, but at least price it competitively with the S25 Ultra. Right now, Apple‚Äôs pricing in India makes zero sense

I have both. I use both not only for my YT content but also for stock content. For photos I only use the iPhone. For zoomed videos, only the iPhone. But the iPhone is only for still or panning video. You can‚Äôt walk with the iPhone without a gimbal, it‚Äôs jittery. That‚Äôs where I stop using the iPhone, as putting it even on a phone gimbal is bigger and less portable than the pocket 3. That‚Äôs when I start using the pocket 3. Walking it‚Äôs a camera and a gimbal in one and way smaller than an iPhone on a gimbal. But then again when it rains it‚Äôs useless so I go back to iPhone for still and pans, as no phone gimbal is waterproof. I record using ProRes on the iPhone in Log. Colors are better but the pocket has a bigger sensor and less video noise. I hope the upcoming pocket 4 will record in a higher bitrate as about 80 that it does now in 24-25 fps is not much. But on the other hand the pocket 3 records in constant frame rate, while the iPhone fluctuates. If you try to record in open gate, in order to get constant frame rate, you lose stabilisation and video denoising. I could go on but I hope you understand why there can never be a winner and as I started mentioning l use both, depending on the scenario.

Digital sharpness? OP3 wins. Size on disk vs quality? OP3 wins. Being able to record yourself with a monitor? OP3 wins. Background blur? OP3 wins - this is very important since the most comun use case would be the vlog and you want to isolate the subject. Audio quality? OP3 wins, especially because you can connect the mics INCLUDING the dji mic 3 with 32bit float as a backup. The big wins for the iphone:  you'll always have it with you and it has multiple focals. Both are amazing, love having them both :P EDIT: if forced to only have one, would go with the iphone if the budget allows...
